    <bioghist id="ref6">
      <head>Historical Information</head>
      <p>The records in this collection are early examples of "electrical" recordings. Prior to 1925 recordings were made acoustically with singers and musicians playing into a horn. Electrical recording introduced the microphone which could pick up a larger range of sound and tone. Record companies developed specific names for this new recording process. The Victor Talking Machine company dubbed the new electric records as Othrophonic Records; Columbia produced "viva-tonal" records. The records in this collection are labeled as such.</p>
      <p>A product of Nipponophone, Orient was acquired by Columbia in 1925</p>
    </bioghist>
